<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-04-29T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-04-29T12:00:00-05:00" n="821" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d821">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">818.6363/112: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">San
                                        José</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-04-29T11:00:00-06:00"><hi rend="italic">April 29,
                                        1922—11 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 11:20
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>15. My telegram number 10, April 15, 2 p.m.<note n="19" xml:id="d821fn19">Not printed.</note> Minister of Foreign Affairs … informed me
                            Special Investigator Esquivel has reported relative to contract of Costa
                            Rica Oil Corporation and according to present plans the President will
                            cancel contract by Executive decree at an early date. Cancellation based
                            on charges one and two reported on page 3 despatch number 274, January
                            4, 1922.<note n="20" xml:id="d821fn20">See “First” and “Second”, <ref target="#pg_996">pp. 996</ref>–<ref target="#pg_997">997</ref>.</note> Corporation maintains forfeiture can be declared
                            only after contractor is heard in his defense.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>